{"type":"message","id":"8c8cf10f","parentId":"c2b601c4","timestamp":"2026-04-05T15:06:54.243Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The service is running on 3001 and listening, but the request is returning a 401. This is very strange - the context-api.js doesn't have any auth logic!\n\nWait - I think I understand now. The OpenClaw Gateway (running at some port) is intercepting these requests somehow. Let me check what happens if I curl with a specific Host header or try a different approach.\n\nActually, let me check if maybe the problem is iptables or some routing. Let me try to check what process is truly listening and if there's something weird going on.\n\nActually wait - looking at the error format again:\n```json\n{\"extra\":null,\"message\":\"Unauthorized\",\"messageId\":\"auth.unauthorized\",\"statusCode\":401,\"traceID\":\"\"}\n```\n\nThis is the OpenClaw Gateway error format! So somehow requests to localhost:3001 are being routed to the OpenClaw Gateway. This is very likely because there's an iptables rule or the Gateway is listening on a wildcard and routing based on Host header or path.\n\nLet me check the Gateway's configuration or see if there's some iptables stuff going on.\n\nActually - one more thing to try: what if I bind to 127.0.0.1 explicitly vs binding to 0.0.0.0? Let me check the current listening address.\n\nActually wait - when I run ss -tlnp, it just shows *:3001 which means 0.0.0.0:3001. If the OpenClaw Gateway is also listening on 0.0.0.0 and has higher priority or is binding after, there could be a conflict.\n\nLet me check the OpenClaw gateway port by looking at how it's configured or if it's running.\n\nLet me try a different port that's definitely not in use.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a9bb2559c3c54b47a4d0d0b3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl http://localhost:3000/api/status 2>&1 | head -5"}}],"api