{"type":"message","id":"c8d8d23a","parentId":"aadc1b36","timestamp":"2026-04-05T15:07:46.903Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it! There's an OpenClaw Gateway running (pid 618). It's listening on ports 18789 and 18791 (HTTP/WebSocket). Also I see port 3100 which might be used for something, and port 3001 is listening on 0.0.0.0 (all interfaces).\n\nBut wait - there's also port 3100 and 5003 open. Let me check what's on these ports. And the gateway is running as \"openclaw-gatewa\" (truncated name).\n\nThe issue is that port 3001 is being listened on by some process. Let me check which one. Actually, actually the 3001 might be our context-api running from the systemd start! But we're getting 401 which means requests are being intercepted.\n\nActually - wait again. The ss output shows state as \"LISTEN\" for 3001 but there's no process shown in the \"Process\" column. That's weird - it should show the process. Unless it's being shown but truncated. Let me look more carefully.\n\nActually looking again, I don't see a process listed for port 3001 in the output. That's weird - there's always a process. Unless it's some weird kernel-level thing or something else.\n\nLet me also check what's listening on 3001 explicitly:\n\nWait, I realize what might be happening. When the openclaw-gateway is running, it might have a catch-all route or proxy configuration that intercepts requests to certain ports or paths and returns 401 for unauthorized requests.\n\nOr more likely - there's some iptables rule or the gateway is acting as a transparent proxy. Let me check if there's a proxy or iptables configuration.\n\nBut wait - I see port 3100 is open and 5003. Let me check what those are and try using those ports instead for our services.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The problem is:\n1. Our context-api.js is running and listening on port 3001 (confirmed by \"Context API on 3001\" output)\n\n\n2. But when we curl localhost:3001 we get a 401 from OpenClaw Gateway\n\nThis suggests that either the OpenClaw Gateway has some config that intercepts requests to port 3001, or there's a proxy rule somewhere. The most likely is that the Gateway has some iptables rules or it's using some kind of network namespace that intercepts certain ports.\n\nLet me try to solve this by using different ports for our services - maybe 3101 and 3102 instead of 3001 and 3002. And also, let me check what is actually happening with port 3001 by using netcat or something to see if it's truly our process listening.\n\nLet me also check if there's some specific reason the 401 is being returned - perhaps the context-api needs to accept some form of authentication or the gateway is configured to reject requests without proper credentials.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d5e2f76a35e5e184e45c1016f1025","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -v http://127.0.0.1:3001/api/context/status 2>&1 | head -30"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"codingplan","model":"minimax-m2.5","usage":{"input":3000,"output":636,"cacheRead":22656,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":26292,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775401628030,"responseId":"019d5e2ee7e957663e947a2b595e312b"}}
